article.headline: Bonner sparks Florida against cold-shooting Tide
article.linkText: Florida bounces back from rout to pound Alabama
article.story: GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida's current stay at No. 1 likely will be short-lived, but legitimate nonetheless. Alabama's visit to the top of the poll earlier in the season seems more and more like a joke every day. Matt Bonner scored 21 points Saturday to help the top-ranked Gators rediscover their winning ways, 75-56 over the slumping (No. 20 ESPN/USA Today, No. 22 AP) Crimson Tide. The Gators (19-3, 8-1 Southeastern Conference), ranked first for the first time in school history this week, lost 70-55 at Kentucky on Tuesday in their debut game as No. 1. "Tuesday morning, we woke up, we were No. 1 in the country and everyone was talking about us,'' Florida coach Billy Donovan said. "By 11:30 that night, everyone was laughing at that. That was an emotional day, and we needed to be able to move forward.'' They did, recovering nicely against Alabama (13-7, 3-6), a team that knows all about a No. 1 hangover. Since making it to the top spot in the Associated Press poll Dec. 23, the Crimson Tide has gone 5-7, including five losses in its last six games. "It was almost a half-joke,'' Crimson Tide coach Mark Gottfried said of the reaction when Alabama made it to No. 1. "It was good for our program to reach that point. But I think Florida is in a different situation. They've got the weapons.'' Freshman Anthony Roberson was brilliant again for Florida, making four 3-pointers to finish with 16 points. He came off a pick and made a running 3 from three steps behind the line with 2:09 left in the first half to give Florida a 36-22 lead. David Lee had 12 points and eight rebounds for the Gators. Bonner snapped out of a mini-slump, cracking the 15-point mark for the first time since Jan. 18. He and Roberson combined for two 3-pointers and 10 points during a 12-6 run early in the second half that gave Florida a 55-36 lead. The game was never in doubt after that. The victory probably won't salvage Florida's top ranking -- its blowout loss at Kentucky took care of that. But it did offer a forceful reminder of how the Gators got there. They moved the ball well, finishing with 19 assists versus only eight turnovers. And once again, their shot distribution was good: Only Bonner shot more than 10 times and all starters got at least five attempts. "To me, the good teams are the ones who can take the setbacks and come right back,'' Donovan said. "I thought our guys did that today.'' Alabama got 15 points from Erwin Dudley and 13 apiece from Maurice Williams and freshman Kennedy Winston. Once again, however, awful shooting was a killer. Crimson Tide players shot 19 times inside the paint in the first half and committed only four turnovers. But they made only six of those close-range shots, and found themselves trailing by 14 at halftime. Alabama shot 32 percent, marking the sixth straight game in which it hasn't shot better than 41 percent. Thus continued a cold streak that has Alabama ranked last in the SEC in shooting percentage during conference play. "Sometimes you find yourself in a period where you're in a funk and you can't get out,'' Gottfried said. "It doesn't leave you with a lot of room for error.'' Florida, meanwhile, made 47 percent of its shots, both overall and from 3-point range. Bonner was the star, going 8-for-14 and playing an inspired game that contrasted greatly with the performance he and his teammates gave in Lexington. "As far as psyche goes, we just focused on the next thing,'' Bonner said. "In this league, you know you can't dwell in the past or else you're going to lose another one and another one.'' Alabama knows. Gottfried is delving into history in hopes of making his team realize there's still something to play for. "You can take Villanova in 1985, NC State in 1983, UCLA in 1980,'' he said, recalling three teams who overcame slumps to make the NCAA finals. "There are all kinds of teams that have found themselves struggling at one point, and still found a way to play well.''
